  "slug": "salade-nicoise",
  "title": "Salade niçoise",
  "subtitle": "The composed salad of Nice: tuna, egg, beans and olives.",
  "excerpt": "A composed salad of tuna, hard-boiled eggs, green beans, tomatoes, black olives and anchovies on a bed of lettuce, dressed with a sharp vinaigrette. Classic Nice in a bowl. Serves four.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Salade niçoise. The dish is the signature salad of Nice and the French Riviera, documented throughout the 20th century in Provençal cookbooks. Traditional versions contain no cooked potato; this is a modern addition. Auguste Escoffier's Ma Cuisine (1934) and Elizabeth David's French Provincial Cooking (1960) both include versions.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A niçoise should be composed, not tossed. Each element is arranged separately on the plate so the diner can see what they are getting. The dressing is sharp, made with more lemon or vinegar than feels comfortable, because the tuna, eggs and anchovies are all rich and need something assertive to cut through them.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The traditional dispute is over potatoes: purists say no potato, the rest of France says yes. Here, there are no potatoes, which makes it faster and lighter, and closer to what the Niçois actually eat.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
