      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cook the beans and eggs",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bring a saucepan of salted water to the boil. Blanch {{green-beans}} of green beans for 3 minutes; remove with a slotted spoon and plunge into cold water. Add {{eggs}} eggs to the same water and boil for 9 minutes. Transfer to cold water, peel and halve.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the dressing and compose",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Whisk {{extra-virgin-olive-oil}} of extra-virgin olive oil with {{red-wine-vinegar}} of red wine vinegar, {{dijon-mustard}} of Dijon mustard and {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt until emulsified. Arrange {{cos-lettuce}} lettuce leaves on a large platter. Lay the tomato wedges, green beans, halved eggs and {{tuna-tinned}} of drained tuna over the leaves. Scatter {{olives-black}} of olives and {{capers}} of capers if using. Lay the anchovy fillets over the top. Drizzle the dressing over everything just before serving.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Troubleshooting",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": null,
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Transfer eggs to cold water immediately after cooking. 9 minutes gives a fully set but vivid yellow yolk.",
              "cause": "Overcooked eggs or not cooled quickly enough.",
              "symptom": "Eggs with grey-green yolks"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Niçoise needs a sharp dressing; more vinegar than feels natural. Dress just before serving, the tomatoes release water if dressed ahead.",
              "cause": "Dressing too timid or applied too early.",
              "symptom": "Salad watery and bland"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Use tuna packed in olive oil; it has a better texture and more flavour. If only brine-packed is available, drain well and drizzle with a little olive oil.",
              "cause": "Tuna in brine instead of oil.",
              "symptom": "Tuna dry and crumbly"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "Common problems"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Nice is the city where Provençal cooking meets the sea, and the niçoise is its edible signature. The salad has been exported so widely that most versions have drifted from the original, but the principle remains: a collection of the best summer vegetables and preserved fish, dressed and served at room temperature. On a hot day, with cold rosé and good bread, it is as good as lunch gets.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
